\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator noted that s\'2Fhe evaluated this programme in April 2010\'2C as one of a package of three that s\'2Fhe was asked to evaluate\'3A BEd Foundation phase\'3B Intermediate and Senior phases\'3B and Senior phase and FET. It has been re-submitted \'284 March 2011\'29. The evaluator stated that it is\'2C however\'2C difficult to re-evaluate it\'2C as all the documents uploaded for the institutional information are dated January 2010. She has\'2C therefore\'2C worked from the Application form for Programme Accreditation alone\'2C which has been considerably revised. The evaluator further indicated that it is far more realistic for the institution to introduce the Foundation Phase BEd \'28which has less subject specific degree-level content knowledge\'29 only. The evaluation is based on the assumption that the BEd \'28Foundation Phase\'29 is the college\'E2\'80\'99s only degree programme envisaged for 2012\'2C but this is not clear. The institution indicated that it will be \'E2\'80\'9Cphasing out of the BEd programmes of the NWU as from 2011 over a six year period.\'E2\'80\'9D\line \line The evaluator indicated that Criteria 1\'2C 3\'2C 5\'2C 6\'2C and 8 meet minimum standards and that Criteria 2\'2C 4 and 7 are in need of improvement. \line \line The evaluator felt that the programme is well founded on a knowledge of early childhood education and pedagogy\'2C with a balance between the theoretical and the practical elements. The structure adopted is that of 49 \'28vs. 73 previously\'29 small modules\'2C typically 6 or 12 credits each\'2C of which almost all are compulsory \'28including two religious\'2FBiblical studies modules\'29 each year. Considerable care has been taken in re-designing the programme and in seeking appropriate advice. The modules cover the three learning programmes of the Foundation Phase NCS and a range of practical and method elements. There is far more detail\'2C both of the programme as a whole and of individual courses than before\'2C and although it does not refer to Draft Policy on Minimum Requirements for Qualifications in Education \'28Department of Higher Education and Training\'2C November 2010\'29\'2C it can probably be adapted to its credit requirements without too much trouble. \line Teaching practice is now properly integrated into the programme 96 credits \'2F 20 weeks \'28although 1.10 states \'E2\'80\'9Cone day\'E2\'80\'9D for the duration of experiential learning\'29.\line The admission procedures are also clearly spelled out and suitable. RPL is treated in more detail than before. \line There is more information available regarding the qualifications of staff\'2C but no further CVs\'2C beyond that of the newly appointed programme co-ordinator. This is a very significant appointment for the programme as she previously lectured in education at UNISA and is very well-suited for the position. There are seven full-time and 10 part-time academic staff members. The academy has a staff-student ratio of 1\'3A8 and projects a future ratio of no more than 1\'3A25\'2C which is generally favourable.\line The teaching and learning strategy is truly mixed mode and many would find it an ideal way to train teachers. Students are expected to be in a learnership-type \'28\'E2\'80\'9Cexperiential learning\'E2\'80\'9D\'29 position in a school for one - three days a week and to attend lectures every Saturday and on some weekday afternoons. The balance of their time is to be devoted to self-study\'2C which is supported by study guides and by a web portal\line The academy is piggy-backed on to a school and hires its premises \'28classrooms and computer centre\'29 after hours. It has an administration building and a 70-seat lecture venue of its own. The library at present consists of \'E2\'80\'9Cat least\'E2\'80\'9D 1000 books and the academy plans expenditure of R80 000 per year \'28increasing by the rate of inflation\'29 \'3D approx. 400-500 books. This is clearly wholly inadequate for the needs of the three four-year Level 7 degree programmes\'2C for either student or lecturer resources. \line The directorate supports the recommendation that the programme should be accredited. \line \cell \pard 

